Dungeons & Dragons 3.5e System Framework: A Definition Document
1. Core Resolution Mechanics

1.1. The d20 System Check
The d20 System utilizes a single, invariant resolution mechanic for all actions, combat included: the d20 check.1
Formula: $\text{d}20 + \text{Relevant Modifier}$ 1
Success Condition: The result must equal or exceed a set target number, known as the Difficulty Class (DC) for passive challenges or the Armor Class (AC) for opposed combat rolls.1
Dice Set: The game employs a set of polyhedral dice, including the d4, d6, d8, d10, d12, and the essential d20.2 Dice other than the d20 are primarily used for determining variable outcomes such as damage or Hit Points (HP).2
Critical Outcomes: A natural roll of 20 typically results in a critical hit (or automatic success), while a natural roll of 1 results in an automatic miss or failure.
1.2. Combat Action Economy
Combat is structured into 6-second rounds, managed by six discrete action types 3:
Action Type
Definition and Usage
Standard Action
The primary action taken on a turn (e.g., casting most spells, making a single attack). A character typically gets one Standard action per round.
Move Action
Allows a character to move up to their speed or perform minor activities. Can often be combined with a Standard action.
Full-Round Action
Consumes the entire round (Standard and Move components). Used for high-impact activities like performing a full iterative attack sequence or casting a long-duration spell.
Free Action
Consumes a minimal amount of time and effort. Can be performed alongside other actions during a turn, but is strictly limited to the active character's turn (except for speaking).
Swift Action
An instantaneous action that takes no more time than a Free action but is generally more powerful. A character is usually limited to one Swift action per round.
Immediate Action
Similar to a Swift action but can be performed when it is not the character's turn.3

2. Character Abilities and Defenses

2.1. The Six Ability Scores
A character’s innate capacities are defined by six Ability Scores, which generate the fundamental numerical modifier for all checks and saves.

Ability Score
Mechanical Function
Strength (STR)
Measures physical power. Primary modifier for melee attack rolls and damage.

Dexterity (DEX)
Measures agility and reflexes. Primary modifier for ranged attack rolls, adds to Armor Class (AC), and governs the Reflex saving throw.1
Constitution (CON)
Measures health and endurance. Determines Hit Points (HP) and governs the Fortitude saving throw.1
Intelligence (INT)
Measures reasoning and knowledge. Determines the number of skill points gained per level.

Wisdom (WIS)
Measures intuition and willpower. Primary casting ability for divine spellcasters and governs the Will saving throw.1
Charisma (CHA)
Measures personality and appeal. Primary casting ability for spontaneous arcane spellcasters (Sorcerers and Bards).


2.2. Ability Modifier Calculation
Every Ability Score is converted into an Ability Modifier, which is added to d20 rolls.
Formula: $\text{Modifier} = \lfloor(\text{Score} - 10) / 2\rfloor$ 6
Baseline: A score of 10 or 11 results in a $+0$ modifier.

Scaling: Every two points gained in an Ability Score results in a $+1$ increase to the modifier.

Maximum: There is no inherent mechanical cap on how high an ability score can progress beyond character creation.

